WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.500
Good morning.

00:03.500 --> 00:05.260
My name is Dan Nebrig.

00:05.260 --> 00:07.700
I'm the executive assistant to our center director.

00:07.700 --> 00:10.040
And on his behalf, I would like to welcome you

00:10.040 --> 00:13.660
to this, the third in a series of 20th anniversary

00:13.660 --> 00:17.820
of Apollo lectures and discussions that we've been having.

00:17.820 --> 00:20.980
The first two dealt with what we knew about the moon

00:20.980 --> 00:23.160
before Apollo, and then yesterday

00:23.160 --> 00:27.540
with the technical planning for the Apollo missions.

00:27.540 --> 00:31.020
Today's sessions cover an aspect of our work here

00:31.020 --> 00:33.340
that is unique to the Johnson Space Center,

00:33.340 --> 00:36.700
that of mission control, and more importantly,

00:36.700 --> 00:39.620
about the planning for the operation of those missions

00:39.620 --> 00:43.300
that are so essential to the success of the missions.

00:43.300 --> 00:44.940
Each of our panelists today is you'd

00:44.940 --> 00:48.100
imminently qualified to discuss the topics

00:48.100 --> 00:51.340
because they have all served as flight directors

00:51.340 --> 00:54.780
or mission controllers during the Apollo program.

00:54.780 --> 00:56.220
Now, of course, later in their life,

00:56.220 --> 00:58.460
they went on to other ancillary positions

00:58.460 --> 01:00.740
like center director and program manager

01:00.740 --> 01:03.020
and a few unimportant jobs like that.

01:03.020 --> 01:05.260
But I'm sure they would all consider their time

01:05.260 --> 01:10.180
in mission control to be among the highlights of their career.

01:10.180 --> 01:12.980
Our moderator today is also imminently qualified

01:12.980 --> 01:14.460
for this subject.

01:14.460 --> 01:18.660
Dr. Joe Allen received his PhD from Yale University,

01:18.660 --> 01:22.580
and in 1967 was selected as an astronaut.

01:22.580 --> 01:26.900
Joe was the on the support crew for Apollo 15,

01:26.900 --> 01:29.220
where he served as the mission scientist.

01:29.220 --> 01:34.340
He was Capcom for STS-1, and then flew as a mission specialist

01:34.340 --> 01:37.260
on STS-5 and 51A.

01:37.260 --> 01:41.260
So he has qualifications from both the ground and flight

01:41.260 --> 01:43.180
to serve on this panel.

01:43.180 --> 01:45.500
I'm sure you've all seen pictures of Joe

01:45.500 --> 01:47.860
tooling around in space in his John to EMU

01:47.860 --> 01:51.660
rescuing distress satellites as we did on 51A.

01:51.660 --> 01:53.820
He is currently the president of space industries

01:53.820 --> 01:55.260
incorporated in here in Houston.

01:55.260 --> 01:57.100
So please welcome Dr. Joe Allen.

01:57.100 --> 02:00.860
APPLAUSE

02:00.860 --> 02:01.860
Thank you.

02:01.860 --> 02:04.060
Thank you.

02:04.060 --> 02:08.700
Dan, thank you very much, and welcome, everyone.

02:08.700 --> 02:12.380
I'm pleased to be the moderator today.

02:12.380 --> 02:14.940
Every group of flight directors needs moderation,

02:14.940 --> 02:19.940
and I've been given that assignment, and I welcome it.

02:19.940 --> 02:21.420
I appreciate it very much.

02:21.420 --> 02:27.780
As Dan said, I was at NASA here at the Johnson Space Center

02:27.780 --> 02:29.140
for a number of years.

02:29.140 --> 02:33.660
And I think my main qualification to serve as a referee today

02:33.660 --> 02:37.620
is the fact that I was also privileged to work in the mission

02:37.620 --> 02:39.420
control for a number of years.

02:39.420 --> 02:41.340
It's a very interesting demanding,

02:41.340 --> 02:47.500
and more often than not an enjoyable assignment.

02:47.500 --> 02:51.140
I worked for these gentlemen on the panel

02:51.140 --> 02:55.460
who were chief flight directors during the Apollo years.

02:55.460 --> 02:59.820
And their assignment for today over the next couple of hours

02:59.820 --> 03:04.700
or so is to recollect, and I quote the instructions given

03:04.700 --> 03:10.420
to us, recollect important aspects of the missions themselves.

03:10.420 --> 03:12.100
They're eminently qualified to do that.

03:12.100 --> 03:14.060
And if they don't remember the important things,

03:14.060 --> 03:17.220
I guarantee they'll remember some of the intriguing things,

03:17.220 --> 03:21.740
and I hope some of the amusing things that occurred

03:21.740 --> 03:24.140
from the perspective of the flight directors

03:24.140 --> 03:27.380
during the Apollo missions.

03:27.380 --> 03:30.340
We're gathered really to observe these missions

03:30.340 --> 03:33.820
and to celebrate the remarkable success of them.

03:33.820 --> 03:42.460
The main intent of today's panel is to celebrate and to enjoy.

03:42.460 --> 03:47.060
And to that end, if you are curious about one or two things

03:47.060 --> 03:50.780
they don't quite explain, please hold up your hand.

03:50.780 --> 03:54.300
And starting very early, I think we'll begin with questions

03:54.300 --> 03:55.020
from the audience.

03:55.020 --> 03:56.780
And I know if you don't have questions,

03:56.780 --> 03:58.900
there are numbers of things I've wondered about

03:58.900 --> 04:03.020
that I will begin to ask about.

04:03.020 --> 04:10.020
My panel members are starting here, Dr. Glenn Loney.

04:10.020 --> 04:16.060
Glenn is from Pennsylvania, from Old Forge, Pennsylvania.

04:16.060 --> 04:18.980
He comes to the space business by way of the University

04:18.980 --> 04:22.580
of Scranton and Detroit.

04:22.580 --> 04:26.580
Glenn began not with NASA, but with NACA,

04:26.580 --> 04:31.340
the predecessor of NASA in, believe it or not, 1958.

04:31.340 --> 04:38.500
He was with the Space Task Group from 1959 to 62.

04:38.500 --> 04:41.740
He came here as one of the original founders

04:41.740 --> 04:46.020
of the Man's Spacecraft Center in 1962.

04:46.020 --> 04:47.820
He was the chief of the flight directors

04:47.820 --> 04:51.500
during many of the Apollo missions.

04:51.500 --> 04:54.460
And through the Apollo years, I went on to serve

04:54.460 --> 04:56.900
in many other capacities at NASA.

04:56.900 --> 04:59.700
And he is now the head of the Rockwell International

04:59.700 --> 05:03.420
Operations here in Houston, Texas.

05:03.420 --> 05:07.700
On Glenn's right is Cliff Charles' worth.

05:07.700 --> 05:11.660
From, I'm told, originally Minnesota, I don't quite believe it,

05:11.660 --> 05:18.540
but only briefly probably spent really much time

05:18.540 --> 05:23.220
in Mississippi came to the Man's Spacecraft Center also

05:23.220 --> 05:24.740
in 1962.

05:24.740 --> 05:30.020
Prior to that, he had been with the Army at KSE.

05:30.020 --> 05:34.700
And it was, it was a cannabral then or what?

05:34.700 --> 05:36.980
That one.

05:36.980 --> 05:38.740
I don't remember back that part.

05:38.740 --> 05:50.020
The cliff was a flight director here of 1962 through 1970.

05:50.020 --> 05:53.660
And also since that time, had many other duties, including

05:53.660 --> 05:57.180
the assignment of Deputy Director of the then Johnson Space

05:57.180 --> 05:57.700
Center.

05:57.700 --> 06:02.540
And he retired from JSC last year.

06:02.540 --> 06:05.780
Next to Cliff, Jerry Griffin.

06:05.780 --> 06:06.620
I know it's Jerry.

06:06.620 --> 06:08.620
Yeah.

06:09.620 --> 06:13.260
From Athens, Texas.

06:13.260 --> 06:17.900
Jerry went from Athens and spent an enormous amount of time

06:17.900 --> 06:20.500
at Texas, A&M.

06:20.500 --> 06:26.300
I think he's still receiving remedial instruction from there.

06:26.300 --> 06:31.540
Was a flight director beginning with Germany 11,

06:31.540 --> 06:34.860
having come to JSC in 64.

06:34.860 --> 06:38.100
And then worked most of the Apollo missions, if not.

06:38.180 --> 06:42.060
Well, I think probably all he was the lead flight director

06:42.060 --> 06:44.740
on 12, 15, and 17.

06:44.740 --> 06:48.020
He went on to many other assignments since that time,

06:48.020 --> 06:50.540
including the director of the Johnson Space Center.

06:50.540 --> 06:56.820
And he's currently with a headhunting firm here

06:56.820 --> 06:59.060
in Houston, Texas.

06:59.060 --> 07:00.060
Not yet successful.

07:00.060 --> 07:02.500
He's not found a gainful employment for me, is yet.

07:02.780 --> 07:09.900
Finally, final panelist, Steve Bales.

07:09.900 --> 07:11.900
Believe me, Steve is the youngest of the group.

07:11.900 --> 07:15.740
He was 20 years younger when Apollo landed.

07:15.740 --> 07:19.700
We all, but Steve was in his early 20s at that time.

07:19.700 --> 07:22.260
He's originally from Iowa.

07:22.260 --> 07:25.380
He went to school in Iowa.

07:25.380 --> 07:29.260
Came here immediately thereafter, I guess, in 64.

07:29.260 --> 07:33.540
It was a flight controller during Apollo known as Guido.

07:33.540 --> 07:38.740
So it was years before I knew his name actually was Bales.

07:38.740 --> 07:41.740
He's now the assistant director, program support,

07:41.740 --> 07:44.340
in the mission's operations directorate.

07:44.340 --> 07:46.580
And with that, I'll turn back to Glenn, who

07:46.580 --> 07:49.460
is the lead flight director on Apollo 7

07:49.460 --> 07:51.860
that really got the Apollo mission started.

07:51.860 --> 07:52.660
Glenn.

07:52.660 --> 07:53.420
Thank you, Joe.

07:53.700 --> 07:54.700
Thank you.

07:54.700 --> 07:55.700
APPLAUSE

08:01.700 --> 08:03.780
I've been asked to start with Apollo 7

08:03.780 --> 08:07.180
because it was the first man flight that we flew

08:07.180 --> 08:09.140
with the Apollo spacecraft.

08:09.140 --> 08:11.340
But perhaps more general than that,

08:11.340 --> 08:14.380
I would talk about it in terms of the events that

08:14.380 --> 08:16.700
led up to Apollo 7.

08:16.700 --> 08:19.660
I think in the minds of everybody here,

08:19.660 --> 08:22.780
up through and including Apollo 7,

08:22.780 --> 08:24.300
we were Earth orbit people.

08:24.300 --> 08:26.740
We were figuring out how to fly spacecraft.

08:26.740 --> 08:29.180
And I think starting after Apollo 7

08:29.180 --> 08:32.980
with the very dramatic Apollo 8, the Cliffle tell us about,

08:32.980 --> 08:36.700
we began the assault on the moon.

08:36.700 --> 08:39.420
Leading up to Apollo 7, we had a number of things

08:39.420 --> 08:42.820
happen in the program that were planned that don't get much

08:42.820 --> 08:46.420
attention and haven't been talked about much in these events.

08:46.420 --> 08:49.740
They were a series of unmanned shots that we had.

08:49.740 --> 08:53.260
We started off with a set of boilerplate vehicles

08:53.260 --> 08:55.500
out in White Sands out in the desert

08:55.500 --> 08:59.700
where we shot up solid rockets to about 30,000 feet.

08:59.700 --> 09:03.420
And then we blew them up and separated the command module

09:03.420 --> 09:05.100
and tested the escape system.

09:05.100 --> 09:08.140
We probably had half a dozen shots out there in the desert.

09:08.140 --> 09:12.180
Some worked and some, by the way, where spooky is the devil

09:12.180 --> 09:14.780
because some of them wanted to come back over the team

09:14.780 --> 09:16.980
that was launching them because of the winds.

09:16.980 --> 09:18.460
So I was kind of an exciting time.

09:18.460 --> 09:21.500
And we learned something about the Apollo escape system

09:21.500 --> 09:24.380
and how it was going to work and how, indeed, we could trust it.

09:24.380 --> 09:27.140
We never actually had to use it in a man flight,

09:27.140 --> 09:30.020
but the Apollo escape system was very reliable

09:30.020 --> 09:31.620
and proven by those tests.

09:31.620 --> 09:35.460
We had a series of unmanned flights called 201 and 202,

09:35.460 --> 09:39.100
which were on the Saturn 1B, which was the smaller Saturn rocket

09:39.100 --> 09:42.540
used for Earth orbital flights and used on Apollo 7.

09:42.540 --> 09:44.700
Those flights were designed to test the heat shield.

09:44.700 --> 09:47.380
There was a lot we didn't know about the aerodynamics

09:47.380 --> 09:51.220
and the heating that would go with a return for the moon.

09:51.220 --> 09:55.180
And we exercised those parameters on a couple of flights

09:55.180 --> 09:57.940
that we called 201 and 202 in the mid-60s.

09:57.940 --> 10:00.020
And we had a lot of fun with those because they were unmanned.

10:00.020 --> 10:02.980
We had a lot of things to do from the control center.

10:02.980 --> 10:05.620
Later on, we flew the Saturn twice unmanned.

10:05.620 --> 10:08.540
Apollo 501 and 502.

10:08.540 --> 10:11.340
They also were very exciting flights.

10:11.340 --> 10:14.900
And the first one went by the book, that was the one I had.

10:14.900 --> 10:18.060
The next one, that Cliff had, almost came

10:18.060 --> 10:23.140
unglued a couple of times and it was kind of a scary flight.

10:23.140 --> 10:26.140
And I'm sure you'll hear more about that during the course of the day.

10:26.140 --> 10:29.060
Before I then moved on to Apollo 7, I would say one more thing

10:29.060 --> 10:34.540
that I think is important about the team and the way we got to the moon.

10:34.540 --> 10:38.940
We had about 10 or a dozen Gemini flights, man flights,

10:38.940 --> 10:41.260
two people in the cockpit.

10:41.260 --> 10:44.260
And when I look back on that, I

10:44.260 --> 10:47.060
think what I realize is that the people who

10:47.060 --> 10:50.700
planned the Gemini program in between the one man, Mercury Capsule,

10:50.700 --> 10:55.100
and the Apollo mission where we had to do so much other kind of work

10:55.100 --> 10:56.260
going to the moon.

10:56.260 --> 10:59.940
They really was a stroke of genius because out of that program

10:59.940 --> 11:02.340
came not so much space hardware.

11:02.340 --> 11:04.460
We used different hardware for Apollo.

11:04.460 --> 11:07.700
What came out of it was the operations team.

11:07.700 --> 11:11.060
If you look at the astronauts that flew the Apollo missions,

11:11.060 --> 11:13.460
I think to a man, almost to a man.

11:13.460 --> 11:15.900
They had all flown in Gemini.

11:15.900 --> 11:19.860
We did launches, rendezvouss.

11:19.860 --> 11:24.860
We didn't use the ejection seats in one very hairy sequence on the pad.

11:24.860 --> 11:27.060
We did rendezvous every way there was to do it.

11:27.060 --> 11:28.100
We did EVAs.

11:28.100 --> 11:29.940
We docked with a genus.

11:29.940 --> 11:31.900
We rode around on chairs, or at least we

11:31.900 --> 11:37.780
tried to, the man-minibring chairs, that we use a derivative of on the shuttle today.

11:37.780 --> 11:41.620
When I look back on that and realize all the different things that we did

11:41.620 --> 11:46.420
that were necessary to know how to do when we went to the moon,

11:46.420 --> 11:51.340
I would say that we came into Apollo with the flight crews and the ground crews

11:51.340 --> 11:52.780
like gangbusters.

11:52.780 --> 11:55.180
It's the word that occurs to me.

11:55.180 --> 11:59.740
We came into the Apollo program with a set of people who had done almost everything

11:59.740 --> 12:02.900
you could do in man-earth orbital flight.

12:02.900 --> 12:05.820
And frankly, we were cocky.

12:05.820 --> 12:07.380
We thought we know how to do this stuff.

12:07.380 --> 12:10.460
And we were looking forward in this assault to the moon.

12:10.540 --> 12:19.100
The events had a tragic and well-known halt with the Apollo fire.

12:19.100 --> 12:23.940
And in the 18 or so months that intervened between that fire and the first

12:23.940 --> 12:28.580
man-flight of Apollo 7, a great number of changes were made to the spacecraft.

12:28.580 --> 12:33.100
And again, the program came out of it much stronger than it otherwise would have

12:33.100 --> 12:35.620
been in the race to the moon.

12:35.620 --> 12:40.780
To finish up this scenario then, as in extending our abilities to operate in

12:40.780 --> 12:43.700
Earth orbit, we had to know that the command service module, which was kind of the

12:43.700 --> 12:46.460
mothership for the Apollo missions worked.

12:46.460 --> 12:52.660
Apollo 7 was flown in October the fall of 1968 with only one more year to go to

12:52.660 --> 12:54.660
meet the president's deadline.

12:54.660 --> 12:57.340
It was about a 10-day flight in Earth orbit.

12:57.340 --> 13:01.820
We did everything we know how to do to the command service module with the three

13:01.820 --> 13:05.660
astronauts and the ground people to test it.

13:05.660 --> 13:10.260
And out of that flight came eventually the plans for Apollo 8.

13:10.260 --> 13:13.900
Actually, a little before the flight we decided we would do Apollo 8, which was the

13:13.900 --> 13:18.620
Frank Bournemont trip around the moon on Christmas.

13:18.620 --> 13:22.660
But when I look back on it, I see that all of those events of the unmanned Apollo

13:22.660 --> 13:28.340
flights, the things that we did in Gemini and the confidence that we gained in

13:28.380 --> 13:33.060
ourselves and our ability to master problems.

13:33.060 --> 13:36.700
We had problems out the galore on almost every Gemini flight.

13:36.700 --> 13:42.060
Out of that kind of a background came the teams of people here and at the Cape, but I will

13:42.060 --> 13:47.580
speak to the teams here, the astronauts and the ground controllers in MCC.

13:47.580 --> 13:51.420
And we really felt confident in going into Apollo.

13:51.420 --> 13:54.420
Apollo 7 was successful, as you know.

13:54.420 --> 14:00.580
We tested the vehicle very well in Earth orbit and then began the exciting phase of the

14:00.580 --> 14:05.420
moon project where we began to test the really big hardware that is the new rocket and the

14:05.420 --> 14:12.460
lunar module and eventually made our assault upon the moon in terms of completing the

14:12.460 --> 14:17.540
lunar landing mission with the team of people that we had built during those early years.

14:17.540 --> 14:20.500
And that team of people was just a cracker jack outfit.

14:20.500 --> 14:27.100
I have always been into this day and overwhelmed with pride at the opportunity I had to be a

14:27.100 --> 14:28.620
part of that team.

14:28.620 --> 14:33.460
So with that, I'll turn it over to Joe and the rest of the guys to tell you after we learned

14:33.460 --> 14:36.980
how to do things in Earth orbit, what we did to go to the moon.

14:36.980 --> 14:38.300
Glenn, thank you.

14:38.300 --> 14:41.540
To take us out from Earth orbit, Cliff.

14:41.540 --> 14:46.620
Yeah, I'd like to start before I get into Apollo 8.

14:46.620 --> 14:53.420
Go back to the thing Glenn mentioned about the second unmanned Saturn V launch.

14:53.420 --> 14:59.540
That flight occurred, I believe, in April of 68.

14:59.540 --> 15:04.660
I may have lost a year or two, but anyway.

15:04.660 --> 15:08.060
We had a few problems that day.

15:08.060 --> 15:13.100
We lost two engines during the second stage in the flight.

15:13.100 --> 15:17.260
We also had Pogo, which nobody knew at the time because we didn't have real time data on

15:17.260 --> 15:21.660
it, but we had Pogo to the extent that the crew wouldn't have been able to read cockpit

15:21.660 --> 15:25.580
gauges and would have probably required an abort.

15:25.580 --> 15:30.540
We had a number of other problems in the spacecraft, but we did stagger into orbit.

15:30.540 --> 15:33.740
And I say that is pretty an accurate description.

15:33.740 --> 15:37.020
We flew all over the sky, but we made it into orbit.

15:37.020 --> 15:44.580
And finally got settled down a couple of orbits later to do the S4B burn to drive the spacecraft

15:44.580 --> 15:48.260
up to come back in and simulate a lunar return.

15:48.260 --> 15:50.860
And lo and behold, it didn't light.

15:50.860 --> 15:57.900
So we aborted off of the S4B and burned the SPS engine, some tremendous long period of

15:57.900 --> 16:03.860
time, and got all we could out of the flight, but we didn't meet the objectives of the

16:03.860 --> 16:05.140
flight.

16:05.140 --> 16:14.140
So that as a background, a meeting occurred over at Marshall in the fall, and I knew there

16:14.140 --> 16:20.660
was a meeting, and I got a phone call one night early to come out to craft office.

16:20.660 --> 16:22.180
He wanted to see me.

16:22.180 --> 16:27.060
Well my first thought was, oh boy, we're going to fly another one of those unmanned deals with

16:27.060 --> 16:29.180
boilerplate on it, and you're elected.

16:29.180 --> 16:31.780
That's what my thought was.

16:31.780 --> 16:37.140
So I walked into his office fully expecting that, and he looked at me and says, what do

16:37.140 --> 16:40.780
you think about taking Apollo 8 to the moon?

16:40.780 --> 16:45.740
And I said, well I haven't thought about it.

16:45.740 --> 16:51.420
But on thinking about it for a little bit, it sounded like a fun thing to try to do.

16:51.420 --> 16:55.860
So he said, I want you to go get certain group of people together, and we need to go get

16:55.860 --> 16:56.860
some answers.

16:57.580 --> 17:02.740
We found out into a team and started looking at all the reasons why you couldn't, and all

17:02.740 --> 17:06.100
the reasons why you could.

17:06.100 --> 17:08.300
This had been going on for some time in the background.

17:08.300 --> 17:12.580
It was initiated by George Lowe and others.

17:12.580 --> 17:17.940
In any event, NASA made that decision, and while Glenn was preparing to fly Apollo 7,

17:17.940 --> 17:24.620
we had a small team off in the center, and many of you probably were on that team, trying

17:24.620 --> 17:30.220
to figure out how to do that, because we had to accelerate a number of things that we

17:30.220 --> 17:35.340
had not planned to do that early, primarily in the software world, some of the trajectory,

17:35.340 --> 17:36.700
kinds of things.

17:36.700 --> 17:41.300
The spacecraft people had a heck of a job trying to go figure out whether they could stamp

17:41.300 --> 17:47.660
this hardware, which we hadn't even flown, really, ready to go to the moon.

17:47.660 --> 17:54.460
Well, all that came together, and we did in fact make the commitment to go.

17:54.460 --> 17:58.740
As Glenn said, leading up to that, we had pretty well proved we knew how to get into Earth

17:58.740 --> 18:03.580
orbit and operate there, but this was the first time we were going to leave Earth orbit,

18:03.580 --> 18:09.860
and go to a place that's three days away in terms of getting back if something happens.

18:09.860 --> 18:15.100
Not only that, we were going to do it without the lunar module, so we would wind up with

18:15.100 --> 18:22.740
a one engine in lunar orbit to get us back home, which was eventually what we had to

18:22.740 --> 18:29.100
do anyway, but it was a little bit spooky if you said and think about that for a while.

18:29.100 --> 18:34.180
The preparations were difficult.

18:34.180 --> 18:42.100
We spent a lot of hard hours working on that, but the day finally came, and we launched,

18:42.100 --> 18:50.700
phase was fairly uneventful, as I recall, and we did our two orbits of preparation to get

18:50.700 --> 18:58.800
ready to go to the moon and burned the HES-4B successfully for TLI.

18:58.800 --> 19:04.340
And from that point on, we had a different ballgame on our hands, for example.

19:04.340 --> 19:09.900
In Earth orbit, most of you, or a lot of you know, you key everything that you're trying

19:09.900 --> 19:16.100
to do on the console, wherever your console is, to when is the next station pass?

19:16.100 --> 19:22.540
You've got about five minutes to seven minutes to get information up and down to the spacecraft.

19:22.540 --> 19:27.740
Well, here we were in a situation where we could talk to him anytime we want to, and that

19:27.740 --> 19:28.740
was a strange thing.

19:28.740 --> 19:34.460
As a matter of fact, I thought about that during the flight because I got to the point

19:34.460 --> 19:38.220
where you'd almost forget they were there, because you know, you could talk to him anytime

19:38.220 --> 19:40.300
you wanted to.

19:40.300 --> 19:49.260
But anyway, the trip out was not uneventful, and these guys feel free to hop in here because

19:49.260 --> 19:51.220
you were involved, too.

19:51.220 --> 19:56.060
One of the things that we had decided to do clever devils that we are was that we would

19:56.060 --> 20:01.060
test that engine on the way out, to be sure they worked right.

20:01.060 --> 20:07.540
And I think we're going to do a small, out-of-plane maneuver just to burp the SPS, and be sure

20:07.540 --> 20:08.540
it was working right.

20:08.540 --> 20:12.020
Well, we did that, and it didn't work right.

20:12.020 --> 20:15.420
And it did not.

20:15.420 --> 20:19.140
And there was a little funny in the thrust chamber pressure.

20:19.140 --> 20:24.400
So now we've got three days to look at data and talk to everybody that you can find in

20:24.400 --> 20:30.460
the world to talk to, to satisfy ourselves that we can indeed commit to put the spacecraft

20:30.460 --> 20:31.460
in a little orbit.

20:31.460 --> 20:35.660
Knowing when we do that, it has to work to come home.

20:36.500 --> 20:41.180
Well, there are an awful lot of smart people today.

20:41.180 --> 20:43.740
Some of them are smarter than we were, I think.

20:43.740 --> 20:46.540
But there were some smart people in.

20:46.540 --> 20:54.780
And they gathered them, whether they be contractors that bowels of a plant somewhere, or the guy that

20:54.780 --> 21:02.620
designed it, whatever it took, and satisfied all levels of management at the Johnson Space

21:02.620 --> 21:08.340
Center and Headquarters, that yes, indeed, we understood what was going on with the engine.

21:08.340 --> 21:12.780
Today, I couldn't explain it, but that we were satisfied.

21:12.780 --> 21:15.940
It was okay to use it and commit to an orbit.

21:15.940 --> 21:18.780
Either you guys, you got anything to add to that?

21:18.780 --> 21:21.420
You some of you were involved in looking at that problem.

21:21.420 --> 21:24.140
I would just add this to it, Cliff.

21:24.140 --> 21:28.100
In retrospect, that was a major systems problem that had to be dealt with and was dealt

21:28.100 --> 21:30.460
with right.

21:30.460 --> 21:34.000
And the situation we were faced with was there was the possibility that after the first

21:34.000 --> 21:38.220
burn, we could have done another little one, and then another little one later to take

21:38.220 --> 21:40.660
it out, but we had to do those fairly quickly.

21:40.660 --> 21:45.860
So there was an urgency to deciding whether we would try another test on the engine or

21:45.860 --> 21:46.860
not.

21:46.860 --> 21:49.540
And it fell to me on my shift to deal with that problem.

21:49.540 --> 21:53.140
Well, at the same time, and I don't even know if this is public knowledge, but at the

21:53.140 --> 21:58.020
same time, there was a report from the crew that one of the crew members was ill.

21:58.020 --> 22:08.220
So, this seemed to attract all of the high management's brains.

22:08.220 --> 22:12.420
Everybody that I thought I could get some help from, they were all off working on the

22:12.420 --> 22:16.420
fact that this guy got sick, which I didn't really care about because it wasn't a bloody

22:16.420 --> 22:17.820
thing that we could do about it today.

22:17.820 --> 22:24.420
I knew of, so just be sick and be quiet about it for God's sake.

22:24.420 --> 22:33.100
So, anyway, while everybody else except the propulsion guys are over here worrying about

22:33.100 --> 22:38.540
this so-called sick astronaut, it fell to me to deal with this issue of well, we're going

22:38.540 --> 22:41.740
to burn this thing another time and see if it works and can we get it and then do a burn

22:41.740 --> 22:44.940
after that to get us back on the trajectory we want and we couldn't do too much because

22:44.940 --> 22:48.020
we were running out of fuel if we did too much of that fooling around and if we're going

22:48.020 --> 22:50.140
to do anything, we had to do it in a big hurry.

22:50.140 --> 22:55.380
So after a whole bunch of deliberations with the people that Cliff talked about, I just

22:55.380 --> 22:59.220
took a deep breath, looked around one more time for the sick astronaut committee and they

22:59.220 --> 23:03.980
were nowhere in sight and said, well, you're right, it sounds alright to me, we're going

23:03.980 --> 23:08.220
to go ahead and we didn't do any burns and we set the track for the Apollo 8 mission,

23:08.220 --> 23:13.540
but Boascher felt like a lone ranger for quite a while there.

23:14.100 --> 23:18.020
Well, can I add something to that?

23:18.020 --> 23:24.100
It so happened that I was kind of riding shotgun on Apollo 8 without a lot of detail to

23:24.100 --> 23:29.180
you so I was put on that sick astronaut committee for you.

23:29.180 --> 23:36.500
And but you got to write one thing to put in context here, we had never left the influence

23:36.500 --> 23:43.300
of our scravity and there was a worry amongst the sick astronaut committee that my

23:43.300 --> 23:49.100
gosh, this means that we there's something that we don't know about heading out of the

23:49.100 --> 23:53.340
Earth's influence and it's caused this astronaut to get sick.

23:53.340 --> 23:59.140
Well as most of you know later on, we've had some some of that almost on every flight,

23:59.140 --> 24:03.620
but it wasn't very serious concern and here was Pearl Glenn wrestling with all the technical

24:03.620 --> 24:08.860
stuff and but we did get finally solved and in fact the astronaut did find a little later

24:08.860 --> 24:12.900
which is the typical pattern once once you get into orbit.

24:12.900 --> 24:15.740
There is the advantage of being the lead flight director.

24:15.740 --> 24:20.500
You see you just delegate all those tufts to the other guy.

24:20.500 --> 24:27.660
In any event, having waited through all of that, we pressed on to the moon and the next

24:27.660 --> 24:34.980
big milestone of course was the first lunar orbit insertion burn and the long wait as

24:35.060 --> 24:39.220
they were behind the moon to find out what happened.

24:39.220 --> 24:44.500
Fortunately, everything went very well but I was one worried individual the first time

24:44.500 --> 24:49.180
they went behind the moon and I know Emel's teacher wouldn't agree with me but it always

24:49.180 --> 24:55.580
spook me to scale at 60 nautical mile orbit to the dam to the moon and see how near that

24:55.580 --> 25:00.220
really is and wanted to know whether you really figured that all out right.

25:00.220 --> 25:08.980
We did, they came around the moon just about the orbit that we had predicted and then they

25:08.980 --> 25:15.900
settled down to about what was about ten orbits I believe of extremely hard work.

25:15.900 --> 25:23.500
We really had some tired crewmen on our hands by the time they left lunar orbit.

25:23.500 --> 25:32.100
We did that, we went ahead and made the burn to head for home and there was a very relieved

25:32.100 --> 25:36.700
group of people and I think Glen Loney was one of the most relieved when we came out

25:36.700 --> 25:41.940
from behind the moon and indeed that engine had worked very well.

25:41.940 --> 25:47.860
I would point out that as an aside prior to going to the moon with the flight so we had

25:47.860 --> 25:51.580
budgeted quite a bit of propellant to do mid course maneuvers because we didn't know

25:51.660 --> 25:56.460
how well we were going to be able to navigate, how well the systems were going to work.

25:56.460 --> 26:02.980
As it turned out they worked very, very well and we had program mid course maneuvers but

26:02.980 --> 26:07.820
they were very small in some cases we skipped them all together and as I recall on eight

26:07.820 --> 26:11.540
that was pretty well the situation we were in both out and back and here is the first

26:11.540 --> 26:16.940
time we've done it so that was very encouraging.

26:17.020 --> 26:24.020
We had some tired crewmen as I said coming back they had elected to try to keep one man

26:24.020 --> 26:31.740
or watch it all times during that particular flight and as we knew we proved once again

26:31.740 --> 26:37.520
that you can't really do that because with the size of the cockpit somebody of weight

26:37.520 --> 26:42.380
keeps the other guys from sleeping very well so they were pretty well beat by the time

26:42.460 --> 26:45.180
they get back to landing.

26:45.180 --> 26:53.680
Landing was uneventful as I recall and I would just summarize Apollo 8 in my mind I think

26:53.860 --> 27:00.860
it was probably as far as I'm concerned the highlight of the Apollo program. The commitment,

27:03.420 --> 27:10.420
the decision it was made to take that step was fantastic in my mind. I don't believe

27:10.740 --> 27:15.260
you could make that decision these days but to think that you're going to take the

27:15.260 --> 27:22.260
second spacecraft out of the shoot send it to the moon and commit to that sort of endeavour

27:23.940 --> 27:30.940
as it took a lot of courage on some people's part to do that. It was a great flight.

27:31.180 --> 27:37.260
One of the more thrilling things to me was the reading of the biblical passages when

27:37.260 --> 27:42.460
the guys were around the moon at Christmas time which was something that they initiated

27:42.460 --> 27:48.260
nobody knew they were going to do it but I can tell you this and there were some tears

27:48.260 --> 27:53.260
in people's eyes when that was going on. It was a great flight I really enjoyed it.

27:53.260 --> 28:01.260
Anybody else glad? Cliff, thank you. Already I'm hearing stories I didn't know about before

28:01.860 --> 28:10.260
I flew in space. I'm glad I'm worrying about them now. Jerry. Well I'll kind of pick up for

28:10.260 --> 28:17.260
Cliff left there and step quickly and kind of bring maybe me and Steve up to the Apollo 11

28:17.260 --> 28:24.260
time frame when we landed on the moon. It's only I agree with what Cliff said that Apollo 8

28:24.260 --> 28:31.260
mission was kind of scary in a way and the reason that it was kind of scary is that in

28:31.260 --> 28:37.260
the courage that he mentioned to take that step is that everything we had done up to that

28:37.260 --> 28:42.260
point with the possible exception of the EVA that we did in Germany we had built a very

28:42.260 --> 28:48.260
careful building block approach. We had one thing at a time and take the next step and

28:48.260 --> 28:55.260
Apollo 8 kind of jumped out of that for a good reason. It pushed the system I think to go on

28:55.260 --> 29:03.260
faster and well within constraints of safety but it showed an ability to take risk and I think

29:03.260 --> 29:08.260
that's where when it's measured and when the gain is worth the risk and I think that's where Cliff and I

29:08.260 --> 29:15.260
really agree that those kinds of things are getting harder and harder to do. But let me get to that

29:15.260 --> 29:21.260
building block approach. Glenn kind of brought you through what built up to get us to Apollo 7 and

29:21.260 --> 29:28.260
for the most part Apollo itself had that same building block approach. After 8 the next thing we

29:28.260 --> 29:34.260
did was Apollo 9 which was a low Earth orbit back in Earth orbit again but we added additional

29:34.260 --> 29:40.260
step to it. We added the lunar module. In the lunar module, in the command module, docked together

29:40.260 --> 29:47.260
like it would be at the moon or in Earth orbit and we undocked them and separated them.

29:47.260 --> 29:52.260
It was the first time we'd ever done anything like that and had two people in the limb, the

29:52.260 --> 29:57.260
lunar module without a heat shield. It was the first time we'd ever had anybody in orbit that

29:57.260 --> 30:04.260
didn't have a protective heat shield to get down and that was a significant step. But we also

30:04.260 --> 30:09.260
had to do that. We could rendezvous, re-dock, transfer the crew back in, discard the

30:09.260 --> 30:15.260
limb and re-enter the command module. That had to be done to return from the moon. That was

30:15.260 --> 30:20.260
another step in the process. Apollo 10 came right after that. We had already been to the

30:20.260 --> 30:27.260
moon on Apollo 8 to go into orbit. Apollo 10 was another, let's go into orbit around the

30:27.260 --> 30:33.260
moon, but it had the lunar module with it which was at another additional step. We did the

30:33.260 --> 30:39.260
thing in Earth, or I'm sorry, in lunar orbit that something like we had done in Earth orbit

30:39.260 --> 30:45.260
on Apollo 9. We separated the crewman, Tom Staff and Jean Sernan went down very low to the

30:45.260 --> 30:50.260
surface but didn't land. But they were close. In fact, some of you may remember Jean Sernan

30:50.260 --> 30:55.260
saying we were really down amongst them and that was because he could see the mountains higher

30:55.260 --> 31:00.260
or at least appearing to be higher like most airplane pilots think they're higher than they

31:00.260 --> 31:05.260
were and they probably weren't. But they were really got down low and then they didn't

31:05.260 --> 31:10.260
abort and came up just like they would have had to in the event of an emergency. But this

31:10.260 --> 31:15.260
one was planned. It wasn't planned to touch down. So here we built another block. They came

31:15.260 --> 31:20.260
back up rendezvous with the command module. Command module did its maneuver and brought

31:20.260 --> 31:28.260
them home. So you can see this step by step creeping up on the problem. And by the time

31:28.260 --> 31:35.260
we launched Apollo 11, as Glenn said, the control team was ready. The launch people

31:35.260 --> 31:42.260
at Cape had been through it several times. The astronauts very well prepared. But there

31:42.260 --> 31:50.260
was a difference about 11. And I think some of us probably, they were involved in it day to day

31:50.260 --> 31:57.260
and I'd like to get the reaction of these guys. I don't think we felt the importance of

31:57.260 --> 32:04.260
it then like we did in later years. This was, and I get back to that building block process.

32:04.260 --> 32:12.260
It was just another step on a goal we had been pursuing for so long that many of us didn't

32:12.260 --> 32:18.260
think of it. I don't think it's being this profound step. We saw it as a great achievement

32:18.260 --> 32:23.260
that we wanted to make happen. But we didn't understand maybe what the rest of the world,

32:23.260 --> 32:29.260
how they felt about it. And we started. I can remember, and I've thought about this

32:29.260 --> 32:33.260
lot in the last week or two because I've had people ask me about it and reporters

32:33.260 --> 32:40.260
wanting to know what it was like. I can remember, although I, on Apollo 11, I was just, I did a

32:40.260 --> 32:47.260
trans lunar shift, a sleep shift virtually on the way out and one on the way back because I was

32:47.260 --> 32:51.260
already assigned Apollo 12 as lead flight director and was already starting to think about

32:51.260 --> 32:58.260
that flight. But I can remember being, although we were on a high step and ready to do it

32:58.260 --> 33:07.260
just like we had on 10, I didn't feel a great difference in the start. I didn't have that

33:07.260 --> 33:14.260
different feeling than I had from 10. And I took it kind of as one step. We've done this.

33:14.260 --> 33:20.260
We've been here. We keep going. And I can remember very clearly where the difference came.

33:20.260 --> 33:25.260
Steve for him, he'll probably talk about some of the alarms that we got on Apollo. Probably started

33:25.260 --> 33:31.260
there for him. It didn't for me because I knew he had that under control and it was a piece of cake.

33:31.260 --> 33:40.260
But what I really remember is when Buzz said we're start to pick up some dust. And I can remember

33:40.260 --> 33:47.260
to this day that I had the realization he's talking about dust being blown off the moon by the

33:47.260 --> 33:54.260
decent engine. And that was the step we had not taken yet. And from there on that

33:54.260 --> 34:01.260
flight had a great different feeling for me. And then surprisingly once we got off the

34:01.260 --> 34:08.260
moon and back up to the lunar orbit point, I felt well we've done this before and it should

34:08.260 --> 34:14.260
be okay. But that interim period was that last step of that building block that we hadn't

34:14.260 --> 34:23.260
done yet. So it put that great difference to it. I think the mission control teams reaction

34:23.260 --> 34:30.260
to the landing is kind of understandable. While there was great euphoria, I think probably

34:30.260 --> 34:37.260
individually. There was no wild screaming or anything like that. In fact, a common-dont

34:37.260 --> 34:44.260
crans was the flight director. And as those of you that know Jean Cran, those of you

34:44.260 --> 34:50.260
don't, I'll tell you a little bit about him. Probably one of the toughest disciplinary and

34:50.260 --> 34:57.260
kinds of guys in the world, very extremely thorough right on top of the situation.

34:57.260 --> 35:04.260
Jean Cran was an international asset and he was just the right guy to be running the control center

35:04.260 --> 35:10.260
that day. He kept a calmness to it. We had some abort opportunities playing there early.

35:10.260 --> 35:15.260
I think we called him T1 and T2. And we didn't know if when the limb touched down it might start to,

35:15.260 --> 35:20.260
one of the gears might start to sink and we might have to punch off immediately. But we did

35:20.260 --> 35:26.260
also have some windows pointed out where we would do these systems checks quickly. And if there was an

35:26.260 --> 35:31.260
opportunity to abort, we had to command module in the right space for them to get back to it.

35:31.260 --> 35:41.260
So it was a very business-like atmosphere and kind of a calm sort of thing. On a personal note,

35:41.260 --> 35:47.260
as soon as we touched down and I realized we had done it and it was all very exciting,

35:47.260 --> 35:53.260
I had started thinking about Apollo 12. Actually before they even had done their EVA

35:53.260 --> 35:57.260
because we had already started talking about what we were going to try to do on Apollo 12,

35:57.260 --> 36:07.260
which was a pretty exacting test. But that built on in the control center throughout that

36:07.260 --> 36:16.260
entire period stay was a very subdued, professional kind of atmosphere. I can remember,

36:16.260 --> 36:21.260
and while I can't tell you exactly what it said, I can remember one humorous note that since I was

36:21.260 --> 36:25.260
kind of working the night shifts, I came in one night and one of our flight controllers

36:25.260 --> 36:31.260
had put up on one of the big screens about size of this thing over here. Some comment not too

36:31.260 --> 36:37.260
kind about the Russians. And other than that, I didn't see any

36:37.260 --> 36:45.260
for volatility in the control center throughout that whole period. Great, great opportunity

36:45.260 --> 36:51.260
in a great day for the country to think about now 20 years later. One final thought

36:51.260 --> 36:57.260
and we were talking about this as we were standing up here before this started today.

36:57.260 --> 37:01.260
One of the things that just amazes me about that whole period leading up to the lunar landing,

37:01.260 --> 37:11.260
and even now to some degree was the youthfulness of that control team.

37:11.260 --> 37:18.260
If I'm not mistaken, I think at that point, the man to my left here was in his mid-30s

37:18.260 --> 37:26.260
and he was the oldest flight director. I won't pin it down to you.

37:26.260 --> 37:32.260
I think he was the oldest flight director, Eve Older than Cranes.

37:32.260 --> 37:38.260
But we were all a bunch of young people. Steve Bales in his 20s.

37:38.260 --> 37:46.260
And when I think about marshalling that kind of energy and vigor in the interest that was shown,

37:46.260 --> 37:53.260
and we still see signs of that today, obviously, we did have a team of management on top of us,

37:53.260 --> 38:02.260
some of them older than that, that were very, very supportive and very visionary and very, very good.

38:02.260 --> 38:14.260
But I think back to the young people that made that happen and kind of marvel that it could have been done by people so young.

38:14.260 --> 38:21.260
We had, Glenn and I know have talked about this. We probably had more responsibility at about age 30

38:21.260 --> 38:29.260
than most people will have in lifetime. And we had that opportunity because NASA gave it to us.

38:29.260 --> 38:30.260
Joe?

38:30.260 --> 38:41.260
Jerry, thank you. Steve, you're kind of the clean up hitter and feel free to correct what any of these old timers have intended to say.

38:41.260 --> 38:45.260
I had to correct them all the time when we were flying, I guess.

38:45.260 --> 38:50.260
Just continuing. I'm actually here representing Gene Cranes. Gene is on his way to Washington today.

38:50.260 --> 38:56.260
And I think, I'd like to say, talk about two things. Because he would want to talk to you about two things.

38:56.260 --> 39:02.260
One was Apollo 9. Jerry mentioned that. It was a very difficult mission and Gene was the lead.

39:02.260 --> 39:08.260
Very difficult because it was sandwiched between probably the greatest mission of the Apollo program Apollo 8.

39:08.260 --> 39:12.260
If you didn't work on Apollo 8, I think you had heartache. I certainly didn't.

39:12.260 --> 39:13.260
And it ate you.

39:13.260 --> 39:15.260
I just didn't know that.

39:15.260 --> 39:20.260
Go without coming to the audience. You have to understand, Mr. Cranes.

39:20.260 --> 39:24.260
Whatever flight he was working on was the toughest flight.

39:24.260 --> 39:27.260
Go ahead.

39:27.260 --> 39:34.260
And on the other side was Apollo 10 where we were going to take the two vehicles and go right down among them as Jerry said.

39:34.260 --> 39:38.260
And here's Apollo 9 and it's going to stay in Earth orbit.

39:38.260 --> 39:41.260
And it's going to do things that are very, very important.

39:41.260 --> 39:45.260
We've never checked out the rendezvous systems. We've done rendezvous in Earth orbit.

39:45.260 --> 39:52.260
We've never used the systems. However, we're actually going to use on the moon to get the two ships back together.

39:52.260 --> 40:00.260
And that was a mission that it took someone very special, I believe, to keep inspiring the team and keep them going.

40:00.260 --> 40:05.260
We are just as excited about Apollo 9 as they would be about Apollo 10 and 11.

40:05.260 --> 40:12.260
And I think it's important that you all realize that between those two outstanding missions there was Apollo 9

40:12.260 --> 40:18.260
and it was just as essential as a building block to go on to 11 as the others were.

40:18.260 --> 40:26.260
The other thing I would like to do is take you back through Apollo 11, the landing and the activation and then leave it on the moon

40:26.260 --> 40:33.260
and then maybe turn it over to Glenn Lennie who actually got them back off the moon back up to the command module.

40:33.260 --> 40:41.260
We'd done a number of things and Apollo 8 was very essential to us because we had a lot of unknowns about how we were going to navigate.

40:41.260 --> 40:53.260
Not just the fact we're going to come so close to the moon but we were really precisely having to put down a ship later when we were going to fly Apollo 11 within a few mile

40:53.260 --> 40:57.260
within less than a mile of a precise point on the moon we wanted to put it.

40:57.260 --> 41:01.260
And the moon is not a nice, spherical place to navigate.

41:01.260 --> 41:05.260
It has concentrations, although in fact they call them mass cons for sure.

41:05.260 --> 41:12.260
And they affected our orbit and we weren't quite sure what techniques we were going to use to actually do the final targeting for the landing module.

41:12.260 --> 41:20.260
Apollo 11, our Apollo 8 taught us how to do that and we actually were able to use those things on 11.

41:20.260 --> 41:35.260
The activation of 11 went so well because we had practiced it on 10 and the new thing and the new part of the game was the actual descent as Jerry talked about.

41:35.260 --> 41:38.260
Now go back to a personal moment.

41:38.260 --> 41:48.260
Before the final descent and the crew was still on the back of the moon, the timeline ran, we would come around the side of the moon, we'd have 15 minutes to look at the spaceship

41:48.260 --> 41:52.260
and then we were going to fire the engine and we were going to land.

41:52.260 --> 42:00.260
10 minutes before acquisition of signal, Jean Krants gave a speech, the general patent we would like to have given.

42:00.260 --> 42:12.260
And I can almost remember it chapter and verse, but the one point that will always stay in my mind is he says, I don't care how we do, we've trained, we know where the best there is.

42:12.260 --> 42:15.260
And whatever happens, I'm going to stand behind you.

42:15.260 --> 42:21.260
And if you think that doesn't mean a lot to a group of flight controllers and a point like that, you just have never been in that situation.

42:21.260 --> 42:23.260
It really means everything to you.

42:23.260 --> 42:29.260
But then right after that, he says, I'm going to lock these doors.

42:29.260 --> 42:38.260
Now, I've never was sure if he was going to keep everybody else out or he's going to keep everybody else in, but he locked the doors.

42:38.260 --> 42:44.260
During the actual descent, there were at least five times when we could have stopped.

42:44.260 --> 42:48.260
And we were very lucky, I think we were lucky, we were prepared.

42:48.260 --> 42:50.260
But in the end, we managed to make it through.

42:50.260 --> 42:53.260
Let me just go through the sequence of that.

42:53.260 --> 42:55.260
We came around the side of the moon.

42:55.260 --> 42:58.260
We were expecting nice, clear communications.

42:58.260 --> 43:02.260
And every other piece of data was garbage.

43:02.260 --> 43:05.260
We about had rough communications with a lot of noise.

43:05.260 --> 43:07.260
We couldn't hardly hear the crew.

43:07.260 --> 43:11.260
And the telemetry was there one minute and it wasn't there the next minute.

43:11.260 --> 43:16.260
And right away, Gene has to decide we have enough data to keep going on.

43:16.260 --> 43:19.260
Fortunately, that's what we've been trained to do.

43:19.260 --> 43:22.260
The simulation people had driven us right to that point many times.

43:22.260 --> 43:26.260
And Gene, old as flight control team.

43:26.260 --> 43:31.260
And collectively, they tried to tell him what we were seeing, what we weren't.

43:31.260 --> 43:36.260
And he made a judgment that we had enough information to keep going on.

43:36.260 --> 43:40.260
We start the descent and right away we find out we have another problem.

43:40.260 --> 43:44.260
Even though we've done the very best we could on targeting,

43:44.260 --> 43:49.260
our ability to predict where the landing module was going to be was an error.

43:49.260 --> 43:51.260
It was an error about four miles.

43:51.260 --> 43:54.260
The guys were coming in about four miles down range from where they thought they were,

43:54.260 --> 43:56.260
from where we'd hoped we were targeting them.

43:56.260 --> 43:57.260
We find that out.

43:57.260 --> 44:00.260
And not only that, we have a velocity air and altitude.

44:00.260 --> 44:05.260
About two-thirds of the way to where we would have to abort.

44:05.260 --> 44:08.260
We're sweating this one out for a couple of minutes.

44:08.260 --> 44:11.260
And during the descent, the way we set up 11,

44:11.260 --> 44:15.260
the crew actually rolled the vehicle around about four or five minutes

44:15.260 --> 44:17.260
into the descent landing radar locked on.

44:17.260 --> 44:19.260
Correct the velocity problem.

44:19.260 --> 44:22.260
There wasn't anything we were going to do about the down range problem.

44:22.260 --> 44:23.260
We're through that.

44:23.260 --> 44:24.260
We're starting to relax.

44:24.260 --> 44:26.260
Relax if you can call it that.

44:27.260 --> 44:31.260
And the crew says I've got this computer alarm.

44:31.260 --> 44:34.260
There is no way you're supposed to be getting computer alarms during descent.

44:34.260 --> 44:36.260
There is absolutely no way you're supposed to.

44:36.260 --> 44:40.260
They're put in there to debug, check out, and do everything else.

44:40.260 --> 44:44.260
But they are not put in there to that kind of alarm to have during descent.

44:44.260 --> 44:46.260
Fortunately again, our training came to our aid.

44:46.260 --> 44:50.260
We had been given those kind of cases a couple of weeks before.

44:50.260 --> 44:53.260
And in fact, when we were given that case in the simulation,

44:53.260 --> 44:55.260
I was ready to write it off and say,

44:55.260 --> 44:59.260
what are we doing, spending our time on this kind of nonsense?

44:59.260 --> 45:00.260
Because it's not realistic.

45:00.260 --> 45:02.260
And I've got other things to worry about.

45:02.260 --> 45:04.260
And Gene said, you will not write that off.

45:04.260 --> 45:05.260
You will form a team.

45:05.260 --> 45:06.260
You will get with the folks.

45:06.260 --> 45:08.260
And you will go through every possible alarm.

45:08.260 --> 45:10.260
I don't care if they're realistic or not.

45:10.260 --> 45:13.260
And you will make up a game plan on how you're going to play it.

45:13.260 --> 45:15.260
So due to the training and due to Gene's insistence,

45:15.260 --> 45:17.260
we had a game plan.

45:17.260 --> 45:18.260
And it was pretty good.

45:18.260 --> 45:20.260
Now, the experts, in this case,

45:20.260 --> 45:21.260
this alarm happened to say,

45:21.260 --> 45:24.260
a computer's got too much to do in this last second.

45:24.260 --> 45:27.260
And the experts had been of some help,

45:27.260 --> 45:29.260
and not a great deal of help on this one.

45:29.260 --> 45:31.260
They said, look, this isn't supposed to happen.

45:31.260 --> 45:34.260
We talked about that for an hour after we got them through that.

45:34.260 --> 45:35.260
After they told us for an hour,

45:35.260 --> 45:36.260
it wasn't ever supposed to happen.

45:36.260 --> 45:38.260
And we said, finally got through to them that,

45:38.260 --> 45:39.260
yeah, but it has happened.

45:39.260 --> 45:40.260
What do we do?

45:40.260 --> 45:42.260
They said, well, it's a very bad situation.

45:42.260 --> 45:48.260
But if it doesn't happen too much,

45:48.260 --> 45:51.260
if it doesn't happen too much,

45:51.260 --> 45:54.260
you're sort of left come up with your own judgment

45:54.260 --> 45:56.260
about what you should do next.

45:56.260 --> 45:59.260
And our own judgment had been,

45:59.260 --> 46:00.260
it wasn't happening that often,

46:00.260 --> 46:01.260
and everything else looked fine.

46:01.260 --> 46:03.260
Navigation looked fine, guidance looked fine,

46:03.260 --> 46:07.260
no more lines, and made a decision to go on.

46:07.260 --> 46:10.260
Now, the crew was distracted by the alarm so much

46:10.260 --> 46:12.260
that they were apparently at this time I didn't know this.

46:12.260 --> 46:14.260
They were looking inside the cockpit,

46:14.260 --> 46:15.260
and they were trying to figure out

46:15.260 --> 46:18.260
maybe they left a switch out of configuration, what had you.

46:18.260 --> 46:21.260
And by the time that Neil looked up

46:21.260 --> 46:23.260
and saw who was going,

46:23.260 --> 46:25.260
this four-mile error that I told you about

46:25.260 --> 46:27.260
had propagated in the fact that we weren't coming down

46:27.260 --> 46:29.260
in this nice smooth place where we were supposed to come down

46:29.260 --> 46:30.260
and we're coming down the Boulder Field.

46:30.260 --> 46:33.260
And he is flying a ship,

46:33.260 --> 46:35.260
as he'd been trained to do over the Boulder Field,

46:35.260 --> 46:37.260
all the time the gas is getting lower and lower.

46:37.260 --> 46:39.260
And if you listen to the other ground,

46:39.260 --> 46:40.260
you hear there's 60 seconds.

46:40.260 --> 46:42.260
That's what it really means, 60 seconds,

46:42.260 --> 46:43.260
and you're going to have to leave.

46:43.260 --> 46:45.260
And then you hear 30 seconds,

46:45.260 --> 46:46.260
and the same thing,

46:46.260 --> 46:48.260
and then there's a long pause even then,

46:48.260 --> 46:49.260
after the 30 seconds,

46:49.260 --> 46:52.260
we're getting down to the 17-15 second frame.

46:52.260 --> 46:54.260
And most people don't realize that,

46:54.260 --> 46:55.260
we're about 15 seconds.

46:55.260 --> 46:56.260
Give or take a couple,

46:56.260 --> 46:58.260
from having to stop the descent.

46:58.260 --> 46:59.260
And then the famous,

46:59.260 --> 47:01.260
I hear, I see the dust,

47:01.260 --> 47:03.260
crew touches down.

47:03.260 --> 47:08.260
And my personal reaction was one of intense relief

47:08.260 --> 47:09.260
and gratitude.

47:09.260 --> 47:11.260
And then it was one of wonder

47:11.260 --> 47:14.260
because the crew said something I'd never heard them say before.

47:14.260 --> 47:15.260
All during a training,

47:15.260 --> 47:17.260
they called themselves the eagle.

47:17.260 --> 47:19.260
Never used any word with eagle.

47:19.260 --> 47:22.260
And then on the day of January 20th,

47:22.260 --> 47:23.260
the three o'clock in the afternoon,

47:23.260 --> 47:25.260
they used the word tranquility base.

47:25.260 --> 47:28.260
And that changed the mission entirely for me,

47:28.260 --> 47:30.260
because we really had a base on them

47:30.260 --> 47:32.260
and a forward outpost, if you will.

47:32.260 --> 47:34.260
And that was, to me,

47:34.260 --> 47:35.260
the most dramatic event,

47:35.260 --> 47:38.260
and the most dramatic thing that was done during that mission.

47:38.260 --> 47:40.260
And we started a lot of problems.

47:40.260 --> 47:42.260
We really didn't know where we were.

47:42.260 --> 47:45.260
I mean, clearly we knew within a some diameter

47:45.260 --> 47:47.260
of where we were on the moon.

47:47.260 --> 47:49.260
But we landed downstream.

47:49.260 --> 47:50.260
Didn't know where we were.

47:50.260 --> 47:52.260
We were going to have to find out where we took off the next day.

47:52.260 --> 47:54.260
And we left all those problems with Glenn Loney,

47:54.260 --> 47:57.260
who had about 10 different sources to tell him

47:57.260 --> 47:58.260
where we were on the moon.

47:58.260 --> 47:59.260
I don't think any agreed.

47:59.260 --> 48:01.260
And he finally decided.

48:01.260 --> 48:02.260
And we kept going.

48:02.260 --> 48:05.260
So I'll turn that back to him.

48:05.260 --> 48:06.260
Go ahead.

