So there were a lot of things that we need to learn about that.

48:54.260 --> 48:56.260
How well can you move around?

48:56.260 --> 48:59.260
How fast can you move and so forth and so on?

48:59.260 --> 49:04.260
And let me put in one story before I get into the surface

49:04.260 --> 49:06.260
activity itself.

49:06.260 --> 49:11.260
There had been a raging debate go on for months amongst the doctors

49:11.260 --> 49:16.260
and the rest of the world about when we land on the moon,

49:16.260 --> 49:18.260
what are we going to do next?

49:18.260 --> 49:21.260
That is, are we going to take a rest cycle with the crew?

49:21.260 --> 49:25.260
Are we going to go ahead and prepare to get out?

49:25.260 --> 49:29.260
Well, the doctors in their judgment felt that certainly we

49:29.260 --> 49:32.260
should have them go to sleep.

49:32.260 --> 49:35.260
There were a number of us who felt that that was going to be

49:35.260 --> 49:39.260
very difficult for anybody to do, having landed on the moon

49:39.260 --> 49:44.260
for the first time in the world to immediately go to sleep

49:44.260 --> 49:47.260
without some help.

49:47.260 --> 49:51.260
So anyway, the doctors won the debate.

49:51.260 --> 49:56.260
And it was baseline that we would in fact have a sleep period

49:56.260 --> 49:58.260
before we did the EVA.

49:58.260 --> 50:01.260
Now, they pointed out several of them, Mr. Griffin,

50:01.260 --> 50:04.260
is pointed out that I'm the elder of this group.

50:04.260 --> 50:08.260
And I was also clever enough to believe that they weren't

50:08.260 --> 50:11.260
going to do that when they got there.

50:11.260 --> 50:15.260
So we had prepared for that eventuality also,

50:15.260 --> 50:19.260
that if a decision was changed and they decided to go ahead

50:19.260 --> 50:23.260
and do the EVA, we'd be ready to support.

50:23.260 --> 50:27.260
Well, sure enough, not too long after they had landed and got

50:27.260 --> 50:30.260
all the switches taken care of and settled down a bit.

50:30.260 --> 50:35.260
We get this radio message that Houston, we think we'd

50:35.260 --> 50:37.260
like to go ahead and do the EVA.

50:37.260 --> 50:40.260
And I'm smiling, you know, because I knew that was going to happen

50:40.260 --> 50:43.260
and I'm kneeling to doctors.

50:43.260 --> 50:46.260
And of course, we said yes.

50:46.260 --> 50:49.260
Well, the only thing in my mind that I did wrong was I had been

50:49.260 --> 50:54.260
up like everybody else for this whole preparation for descent

50:54.260 --> 50:57.260
and lunar descent and I had fixed myself where I had

50:57.260 --> 51:00.260
to pull a whole shift on the moon.

51:00.260 --> 51:02.260
So it made for a long day.

51:02.260 --> 51:06.260
But anyhow, it took a while being first time we did it.

51:06.260 --> 51:11.260
And the limb was very cramped to get all that gear on and checked out.

51:11.260 --> 51:15.260
And as I recall, it seemed like forever to get the cab and define the

51:15.260 --> 51:18.260
depress to the point where they could open hatch at the last two

51:18.260 --> 51:22.260
tenths of a PSI or something that seemed like it took forever.

51:22.260 --> 51:29.260
But Neil got out and I recall my own reaction when he got out

51:29.260 --> 51:33.260
and on to the surface of the moon and looking at it on that TV,

51:33.260 --> 51:36.260
I said, this just doesn't seem real.

51:36.260 --> 51:39.260
You know, and here I am sitting here in the middle of all this.

51:39.260 --> 51:42.260
And it just didn't seem real.

51:42.260 --> 51:44.260
But in fact, it was.

51:44.260 --> 51:46.260
They said about to do their job.

51:46.260 --> 51:49.260
And as usual, we had overprogrammed the timeline.

51:49.260 --> 51:53.260
We had put more stuff in there than three people could probably do.

51:53.260 --> 51:55.260
That they did the best they could.

51:55.260 --> 52:01.260
They also had to stop and take a phone call from somewhere down here in the White House area.

52:01.260 --> 52:05.260
And we had a carefully laid out plan that we were going to have.

52:05.260 --> 52:09.260
I believe there were two types of samples, documented samples, which took quite a

52:09.260 --> 52:14.260
bit of time and what we call grab samples where you just grab raw.

52:14.260 --> 52:21.260
Now, we only had about two hours and 30 minutes program to be out on the moon for this first flight.

52:21.260 --> 52:24.260
And again, we were playing it very conservatively.

52:24.260 --> 52:30.260
We could have stayed longer, but we felt let's do what we have to do that is of significance,

52:30.260 --> 52:38.260
which was deploy a scientific package and gather some samples and get back in while we're ahead.

52:38.260 --> 52:46.260
So I think the guys did a fantastic job of doing the best job they could in a new environment,

52:46.260 --> 52:49.260
in a very compressed timeline.

52:49.260 --> 52:58.260
And with the distractions which were not of their doing, I still think they came out of it with really a wealth of information.

52:58.260 --> 53:01.260
And they really did a great job.

53:01.260 --> 53:05.260
The lunar surface thing, again, was entirely new to us.

53:05.260 --> 53:13.260
We'd spent many hours practicing it, it's difficult to simulate that, but we could in some ways.

53:13.260 --> 53:21.260
And we even had practice astronauts that would get on the phone with us.

53:21.260 --> 53:28.260
And we'd play the what if games on the moon, just like we would do in rendezvous or any other operation.

53:28.260 --> 53:33.260
Again, we spent about two hours and 35 minutes, I believe it was.

53:33.260 --> 53:40.260
I was very, very relieved to see that cabin start to pressurize to get them back in there.

53:40.260 --> 53:49.260
At that point, I felt like we had done it, because I had complete confidence that we could in fact rendezvous with the mothership,

53:49.260 --> 53:55.260
and we had done those things before, and I was very confident that we had it made at that point.

53:55.260 --> 54:01.260
I was always very nervous when they were outside the spacecraft in Earth orbit or on the moon,

54:01.260 --> 54:10.260
because when you stop and think that one seems like flimsy suit that you guys wear.

54:10.260 --> 54:16.260
And unluckily as a flight director, I seemed to manage to have to terminate most of the EVAs in Germany.

54:16.260 --> 54:18.260
So I was kind of nervous about that whole operation.

54:18.260 --> 54:26.260
So I was very glad when they got back in and pumped that cabin up, and you had two very, very tired astronauts at that point.

54:26.260 --> 54:29.260
And a heck of a lot of tired ones on the ground, too.

54:29.260 --> 54:40.260
And with that point, I think we did in fact manage to get them to sleep for a while, and Glenn Schiff was to get them back to the command service module.

54:43.260 --> 54:47.260
Getting ready for Ascent and Lunar Orbiter rendezvous.

54:48.260 --> 54:50.260
There was one thing about Ascent.

