was just one way, there was just one way to do it, and it had to work.

55:05.260 --> 55:11.260
For that reason, the Ascent Engine got a lot of attention like a lot of other things did,

55:12.260 --> 55:17.260
but a lot of attention, and there was a great deal of worry about it, et cetera, et cetera, in terms of getting off the moon.

55:17.260 --> 55:28.260
For me, and probably for the flight controllers in the MCC, our job is kind of outlined by what decisions might we have to make.

55:28.260 --> 55:36.260
For example, during the launch phase, there's a possibility of all kinds of abort decisions or other kind of decisions have to be made.

55:37.260 --> 55:41.260
And it kind of loads you up with a set of possibilities, a set of options, a set of dealing with them.

55:41.260 --> 55:43.260
Countdowns are like that, too.

55:43.260 --> 55:48.260
But for us, at least, and especially for me, on the lunar surface, we didn't have any choices to make.

55:48.260 --> 55:53.260
We just had to get the thing all set up right, be sure all the navigation was right, and then go for it.

55:53.260 --> 55:56.260
There were any decisions to make, the thing had to work.

55:56.260 --> 56:02.260
And that's what happened. The Ascent Engine worked fine, and when we finished with it, we were in Lunar Orbiter.

56:02.260 --> 56:14.260
At that time, I felt we were on the downhill side of the mission because this team of people here and the astronauts, we had done EVA every way from Sunday at Night EVA, rendezvous.

56:14.260 --> 56:19.260
Every way from Sunday during a Gemini program, we did them upside down, backwards, left-handed, right-handed.

56:19.260 --> 56:23.260
And we really felt like we knew how to do that.

56:23.260 --> 56:29.260
And besides that, we had Buzz Aldrin on board who had invented the major part of the techniques that we used.

56:29.260 --> 56:34.260
So we were very confident about our ability to do the Lunar Orbiter rendezvous.

56:34.260 --> 56:38.260
Apollo Tan, of course, had added to that in the Lunar Environment.

56:38.260 --> 56:43.260
So getting through the Ascent phase was just no choice, no decisions to make.

56:43.260 --> 56:48.260
Just hang on to the console for six minutes and pray.

56:48.260 --> 56:52.260
And we did that. The Lunar Orbiter rendezvous went well.

56:52.260 --> 57:04.260
And then the guys started transferring back into CSM for the eventual return back to this planet that we live on called Earth.

